Computing the RKHS Norm of the Representer
The RKHS norm of the representer admits the closed-form expression
\[\begin{gather*}
\boxed{\; \|\psi\|_{\mathcal H_k}^2 = \iint_{\mathcal X\times\mathcal X} k(x,y)\bigl(w(x)-1\bigr)\bigl(w(y)-1\bigr)\,d\nu(x)\,d\nu(y). \;}
\end{gather*}\]
This quantity depends only on the sampling design and the chosen covariance kernel. In practice, we can use a non-stationary GP covariance function as the kernel.
Since the sampling density \(w\) is unknown, it must first be estimated from the observed float locations. Once an estimate \(\hat w\) has been obtained, the double integral can be evaluated numerically using quadrature or Monte Carlo integration. If \(x_1,\ldots,x_m\) are grid points sampled approximately uniformly with respect to \(\nu\), then
\[\begin{gather*}
\|\hat\psi\|_{\mathcal H_k}^2 \approx \frac1{m^2}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\sum_{j=1}^{m} k(x_i,x_j)(\hat w_i-1)(\hat w_j-1).
\end{gather*}\]
